<CHARACTERISTICS_OF_STUDIES>
<CHARACTERISTICS_OF_INCLUDED_STUDIES SORT_BY="STUDY" USER_DEF_1_ENABLED="NO" USER_DEF_2_ENABLED="NO" USER_DEF_3_ENABLED="NO">
<INCLUDED_CHAR STUDY_ID="STD-George-1993">
<CHAR_METHODS>
<P>Six pairs of villages, matched by caste, access to main road, cropping practice, and distance to rural clinics.<BR/>Randomization within each pair. <BR/>No blinding.<BR/>Anthropometric measurement was done by trained field workers at home every 4-5 months.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_METHODS>
<CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<P>Location: India<BR/>Preschool children and all babies born after initiation of the study in the 12 villages. Follow up until 60 months of age.<BR/>N (intervention)=515; N (control)= 505.<BR/>Children with severe congenital anomalies were excluded.</P>
</CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<CHAR_INTERVENTIONS>
<P>Growth monitoring group: monthly weighing by village worker Protocol for advice and other action when growth faltered.<BR/>No growth monitorng group: No routine growth measurement.<BR/>Growth monitoring were performed at home by community nutrition workers. <BR/>Both groups received nutrition education programme, immunisation, deworming, and curative care at weekly rural clinics.</P>
</CHAR_INTERVENTIONS>
<CHAR_OUTCOMES>
<P>Z-scores of weight for age; height for age and weight for height.<BR/>Mean weight gain and height gain per month.</P>
</CHAR_OUTCOMES>
<CHAR_NOTES>
<P>Nutrition workers were selected, one mother from each village and had 2 months training.<BR/>Growth monitoring was started 8 months later than other interventions as it was not accepted by the communities at first.<BR/>Take-up rate was about 90%<BR/>Overall level of malnutrition in the area initially was high.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_NOTES>
</INCLUDED_CHAR>
<INCLUDED_CHAR STUDY_ID="STD-Ruel--1990">
<CHAR_METHODS>
<P>Sequential assignment of mothers at the primary health care clinics.<BR/>No blinding.<BR/>The enrollment period lasted 6 months.<BR/>Pre- and post test scores on maternal knowledge about growth charts were compared between groups.</P>
</CHAR_METHODS>
<CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<P>Location: Lesotho, Southern Africa<BR/>1221 mothers with a child aged &lt;=2 years attending at 9 primary health care clinics in Lesotho.<BR/>335/1221 loss to follow up: 27% of chart group and 29% of no-chart group.</P>
</CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<CHAR_INTERVENTIONS>
<P>Intervention: Growth monitoring using growth chart for counselling of mothers, either Surveillance Growth Chart (group 1) or Road to Health Chart (group 2).<BR/>Control: Children weighed but growth not discussed with the mothers.<BR/>Nutrition education activities were undertaken monthly in all groups.</P>
</CHAR_INTERVENTIONS>
<CHAR_OUTCOMES>
<P>How well mothers interpreted dummy growth patterns presented to them (whether growing well/not well; understanding of weight gain and percentile lines). Data analysed by mean scores, adjusted for baseline knowledge.</P>
</CHAR_OUTCOMES>
<CHAR_NOTES/>
</INCLUDED_CHAR>
